    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Neutrophilia, an increase in neutrophils, is a hallmark finding often associated with acute bacterial infections, where the body mounts a rapid, robust response. Conversely, lymphocytosis, an elevated count of lymphocytes, is frequently seen in response to chronic infections, particularly viral illnesses. While both indicate an immune response, the specific shift in the differential helps clinicians narrow down the likely underlying etiology—acute bacterial versus chronic viral.",
      "source": "target",
